/boot - hold bootloader files essential for system startup
/proc - provides access to kernel and process information dynamically
/sys - exposes kernals view of system's hardware configuration.
/var - stores variable data such as logs, caches, nd temp files.
/usr - contains user-accessible programs and data
/lib - holds essential sys libaries.
/dev - provides device files for interacting with hardware
/etc - stores sys-wide config files
/opt - typically contains optional or 3th party software packages.
/bin - Houses essential user command binaries.
/sbin - Contains essential system administration binaries.
/home - stores user home directories.
/media - mount point for removable media such as usb drives
/mnt - directories for temp mounting filesystems.
/root - home directory for the root user.
/tmp - holds files created by programs or users.

